<div class="sub-content-header">Technology and Emerging Countries Panelists Announced</div>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<i><span class="smallText">Nov 13, 2008 05:08:22</span></i>

<br /><br />

Intel Chairman Craig Barrett and Cisco Chairman and CEO John Chambers will speak at the 2009 International CES as part of the second annual Technology and Emerging Countries Program (TEC), January 9, 2009, from 1-4 pm. TEC focuses on the role technology plays to further economic growth. <BR>&nbsp;<BR>An hour long panel discussion, <STRONG>Reaching the Promise of Universal Access to Technology: Creating the Global Tech Ecosystem</STRONG>, will immediately follow Barrett’s keynote address. The panel focuses on how universal access to technology is the catalyst to greater knowledge, more vibrant market places and growing standards of living. The panel will be moderated by <A href="/docs/Eric_S._Nonacs.pdf" target=_blank>Eric Nonacs</A>, Managing Director for Global Affairs, Endeavour Financial Ltd. Nonacs serves as a Senior Advisor to the William J. Clinton Foundation.&nbsp; From June 2002 until August 2007, he was the Foreign Policy Advisor to President Bill Clinton.&nbsp; <BR>&nbsp;<BR>Panelists include <A href="/docs/Kazi_Islam.pdf" target=_blank>Kazi Islam</A>, CEO of Grameen Solutions. Islam drives Grameen Solution’s vision to build partnerships with global technology companies to jointly create technology based jobs, products, services and solutions for the developing world. <A href="/docs/Michael_Fairbanks.pdf" target=_blank>Michael Fairbanks</A>, Co-founder of the SEVEN Fund. Fairbanks co-authored Harvard Business School's landmark book on business strategy in emerging markets, <EM>Plowing the Sea, Nurturing the Hidden Sources of Growth in Developing Nations</EM>. <A href="/docs/William_Kamkwamba.pdf" target=_blank>William Kamkwamba</A>, Inventor. Kamkwamba, a native of Malawi, achieved international acclaim when he built a windmill with a broken bicycle, tractor fan blade, shock absorber, and blue gum trees to power his family’s home and obviate their need for kerosene. He is the subject of a documentary short film <EM>Moving Windmills</EM> and one of a dozen innovators featured in a new exhibit Driving Force: Visionaries Redefining our World, which opened in September at the Museum of Science and Industry in Chicago. <BR>&nbsp;<BR><A href="http://www.cesweb.org/sessions/keynotes.asp" target=_blank>Learn more about this exciting program!</A> 
